Boil @water{500%ml} (double for 4p) in a #pot or #kettle if you've got one.

Thinly slice the @mushrooms{250%grams}.

Trim and coarsely grate the @carrot{1} (no need to peel).

Trim and thinly slice the @scallion{1}.

Chop the @lemon{1} into thick wedges.

Place a large #pot over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When hot, add the mushrooms and fry until turning golden, ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring
occasionally. Add more oil if necessary.

Stir in the @red Thai style paste{1%sachet} and the carrot.

Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @coconut milk{1%pack}, @vegetable stock{1%sachet}, boiled water and
@sugar{1/4%tsp} (double for 4p) into the pot.

Bring to the boil then reduce to a simmer.

Pop in the @udon noodles{300%grams} and @prawns{180%grams}. IMPORTANT: Wash your
hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. Prawns are cooked when pink on the
outside and opaque in the middle.

Stir, and simmer for ~{6-7%minutes}. Add more water if needed to achieve desired
consistency.

Divide the soup between your #bowls{}.

Season to taste with lemon juice, @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Finish with a sprinkling of @cashews{10%grams} and sliced scallion.

Serve any lemon wedges alongside.

> Red Thai curry paste is usually made up of chilli peppers, garlic and lemongrass
> among other things. It's one of the spicier types of Thai curry, but luckily in
> this soup, it's tempered with cooling coconut milk and paired with prawns for a
> beautifully balanced dish.